04327nam a22006495i 9780271056739DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710567397 a10.1515/97802710567392doi  a(DE-B1597)583818  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE185.86b.S586 2011 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a305.8962221 aShotwell, Alexis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKnowing Otherwise :bRace, Gender, and Implicit Understanding /cAlexis Shotwell. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tPart one. Mapping Implicit Understanding -- tOne Theories of Implicit Understanding -- tTwo Racialized Common Sense -- tThree. An Aesthetics of Sensuousness -- tPart two Navigating Transformations -- tFour Negative Affect and Whiteness -- tFive Enacting Solidarity -- tSix A Knowing That Resided in My Bones -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrejudice is often not a conscious attitude: because of ingrained habits in relating to the world, one may act in prejudiced ways toward others without explicitly understanding the meaning of one's actions. Similarly, one may know how to do certain things, like ride a bicycle, without being able to articulate in words what that knowledge is. These are examples of what Alexis Shotwell discusses in Knowing Otherwise as phenomena of "implicit understanding." Presenting a systematic analysis of this concept, she highlights how this kind of understanding may be used to ground positive political and social change, such as combating racism in its less overt and more deep-rooted forms. Shotwell begins by distinguishing four basic types of implicit understanding: nonpropositional, skill-based, or practical knowledge; embodied knowledge; potentially propositional knowledge; and affective knowledge. She then develops the notion of a racialized and gendered "common sense," drawing on Gramsci and critical race theorists, and clarifies the idea of embodied knowledge by showing how it operates in the realm of aesthetics. She also examines the role that both negative affects, like shame, and positive affects, like sympathy, can play in moving us away from racism and toward political solidarity and social justice. Finally, Shotwell looks at the politicized experience of one's body in feminist and transgender theories of liberation in order to elucidate the role of situated sensuous knowledge in bringing about social change and political transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBlacksxRace identity. 0aGender identity. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271056739zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056739.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK